                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d82">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.04551/20: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Herrick</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-04-30T18:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 30, 1926—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>109. Embassy’s despatch No. 6233, April 9, in regard to proposed convention
                    concerning letters rogatory. Endeavor to ascertain and report to Department (1)
                    the reason for Foreign Office’s sudden unexplained change of attitude; (2)
                    whether the French Government is averse to concluding any convention on letters
                    rogatory; or (3) whether the French Government would be willing to sign an
                    amended form of the draft submitted to it by the Department. If affirmative
                    response obtained to point (3), report changes in draft which Foreign Office
                    would accept.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
